You could use a [Set][1], this will prevent duplicates.

```
function search (keyword, array){
    var result = new Set();
    for(let i = 0; i &lt; array.length; i++) {
        for (key in array[i]) {
            if(array[i][key].includes(keyword)){
                result.add(array[i]);
            }
        }
    }
    return Array.from(result);
}
```


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Set

Improved version of Danny Buonocore code.

 - No accidental global variables.
 - Uses [forEach][1] to iterate over the array.
 - Uses [for...of][2] and [Object.values()][3] to iterate over the values of the object (using [for..in][4] iterates over all non-Symbol, enumerable properties of an object itself and those the object inherits from its constructor&#39;s prototype and are cause for many bugs)
 - &quot;short circuit&quot; the test for adding an object: if a value has matched, there is no need to check the other values. This alone would probably solved your problem, but using a `set` will prevent duplicates if you have the same object multiple times in your array.  


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function search (keyword, array){
      var result = new Set();
      array.forEach( object =&gt; {
        for (const value of Object.values(object)) {
          if ( value.includes(keyword) ) {
            result.add(object);
            continue; // Don&#39;t need to check more on this item.
          }
        }
      });
      return Array.from(result);
    }

    console.log(search(&quot;yes&quot;, [
      { key1 :&quot;yes&quot;, key2:&quot;yes&quot; },
      { key1 :&quot;no&quot;, key2:&quot;no&quot; }
    ]));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/forEach
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for...of
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/values
  [4]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/for...in

